    - m_Type: 0
      Title:
        m_Untranslated: Line 37 - Moving Objects with (the) Force
      Text:
        m_Untranslated: "<code>\r\nVector2 thrust = transform.up * thrustSpeed;\r\nGetComponent&lt;Rigidbody2D&gt;().AddForce(thrust);\r\n</code>\r\nThe
          final <c>if</c> statement on <b>line 31</b> checks if the player is holding
          the up arrow key or the W key. When this action occurs, the player ship
          should thrust forward. To accomplish this, the PlayerMovement script interacts
          with Unity\u2019s physics system using the <doc>Rigidbody2D</doc> component
          on the player game object.\r\nWe know that Rigidbody2D Components are how
          we get Game Objects moving around, either by leaving gravity on and they\u2019ll
          fall (like we did in the first introduction practical) or by turning gravity
          off and getting a Script to start them moving (like we did in the Invaderoids
          practical).\r\nIn the editor the Rigidbody2D Component just allows us to
          set up the parameters of how we want the Game Object to interact with the
          physics system, but it doesn\u2019t allow us to set any initial velocity
          (direction and speed of movement) or any rotational forces.\r\nTaking a
          look at the Rigidbody2D class description (<a>http://docs.unity3d.com/ScriptReference/Rigidbody2D.html</a>
          ) shows that all of the Properties visible in the Inspector are provided,
          but also other ones such as velocity and angularVelocity to describe its
          motion and rotation.\r\nSee the following for more information:\r\n\u2022
          Rigidbody 2D: <a>https://unity3d.com/learn/tutorials/topics/2d-game-creation/rigidbody-2d</a>\r\n"
